Implementing a professional task orchestrator in Unity requires bridging the Unity UI Toolkit with the Azure DevOps REST API and Microsoft Graph API. 

1. Unified Dashboard Architecture 
To create an "active listing" within your project menu, use the UI Toolkit's ListView component. This system efficiently handles dynamic data binding, ensuring your project list stays updated as the backend changes. 
Task Option Menu: Create a right-click or hover "Options" panel using a VisualElement styled with USS for a sleek, enterprise look. 
Active Project Listing: Use a ListView to populate tasks. Bind each entry to a C# class that stores unique task IDs. 
Navigation Logic: When a task is clicked, use a UI Mediator script to hide the list and activate a "Detail View" panel populated with that task's specific data. 

2. Task Detail & Backend Logic 
The "Detailed Overview" screen should display comprehensive data fetched via REST API calls. 
Feature Implementation Detail Source 
Commits & Tags Fetch from _apis/git/repositories/{id}/commits and wit/tags. Microsoft Learn 
Dependencies Use $expand=relations in work item calls to map Parent/Child links. Stack Overflow 
Rootplanner Map Azure "Delivery Plans" or "Roadmaps" to visual timelines in Unity. YouTube: Azure Boards 
Generative Steps Use a custom logic layer to parse "Parent" work items into sub-task lists based on tags. Microsoft Learn 
 
3. Time Management & Schedule Sync 
To connect appointments and agenda data, integrate the Microsoft Graph API. 
Email & Agenda Sync: Use the Calendar API to retrieve events for a specified time range. This allows your dashboard to show upcoming project deadlines directly alongside your personal schedule. 
Detailed Task Planning: Include fields for "Estimated Price" and "Time Management" in the Azure work item custom fields. Fetch these using the Work Item Tracking API. 
Source Links: Attach URLs as "Hyperlinks" in Azure work item relations; Unity can then open these via Application.OpenURL() when clicked. 

4. Implementation Steps 
Register App in Azure AD: Obtain a Client ID and Secret to authenticate with Microsoft Graph and Azure DevOps. 
C# API Client: Write an asynchronous script using UnityWebRequest or HttpClient to fetch JSON data from Azure. 
UI Data Binding: Map the JSON response to a Serializable class in Unity, then bind these fields to your UI Toolkit elements. 
Would you like a specific C# code snippet for the Azure DevOps API authentication or the USS styling for the task detail screen? 
